 policymakers hope that family-friendly law and policy changes will not only increase women's participation in the workplace, but also help women experience greater workplace equality. As Hampson shows, however, these policies and women's abilities to understand and utilize them have fallen short of fully alleviating the tensions that women across the nation are still grappling with as they try to reconcile their work and family responsibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aMothersxEmploymentxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aMothersxEmploymentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aWomen college teachersxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aWomen college teachersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aWork and familyxUnited States. 0aWork and familyzUnited States. 0aWorking mothersxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aWorking mothersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 4aFamily. 4aLegal Consciousness. 4aMilitary. 4aPublic Policy. 4aUniversity. 4aWork/Life Balance. 4aWorking Mothers. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360217540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602175423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602175.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles